## Move Raspberry Pi OS from SD Card to NVMe

This guide documents how to migrate a running Raspberry Pi OS installation from an SD card to an NVMe SSD on a Raspberry Pi 5.

## Goal:

SD card  →  NVMe SSD (system disk)

After migration the Pi boots directly from NVMe.

## 1. Install Raspberry Pi OS (initial boot)

Flash Raspberry Pi OS Lite to the SD card using Raspberry Pi Imager.

Boot the Pi and connect via SSH.

Verify the system disk:

command: lsblk

Expected:

mmcblk0
├─mmcblk0p1 /boot/firmware
└─mmcblk0p2 /

 ## 2. Verify NVMe drives are detected

Example:

nvme0n1
nvme1n1

These are the two SSDs connected through the NVMe adapter.

 ## 3. Configure bootloader to allow NVMe boot

Open Raspberry Pi configuration:

command: sudo raspi-config

Navigate:

Advanced Options
   → Boot Order
      → NVMe/USB Boot

This configures the EEPROM bootloader to attempt NVMe boot before SD.

 ## 4. Fix NVMe controller power-management issue

Some NVMe drives crash due to PCIe power states on Raspberry Pi 5.

Edit the kernel command line:

command: sudo nano /boot/firmware/cmdline.txt

Append to the end of the single line:

nvme_core.default_ps_max_latency_us=0 pcie_aspm=off pcie_port_pm=off

Example:

... rootwait cfg80211.ieee80211_regdom=GB nvme_core.default_ps_max_latency_us=0 pcie_aspm=off pcie_port_pm=off

Save and reboot:

sudo reboot

Verify NVMe stability:

command: dmesg | grep -i nvme

You should no longer see:

controller is down
I/O error
reset failure

## 5. Clone the SD card to NVMe

Clone the entire SD card to the NVMe SSD.

SD → nvme0n1

Run:

command: sudo dd if=/dev/mmcblk0 of=/dev/nvme0n1 bs=64M status=progress conv=fsync

## Explanation: 
- sudo: Runs the command with administrator privileges. Required because you're accessing raw storage devices.
- dd: A low‑level copying tool. Nickname: “disk destroyer” — because a single mistake can wipe the wrong drive.
- if=/dev/mmcblk0: Input file → the source device. This is your microSD card.
- of=/dev/nvme0n1: Output file → the destination device This is your NVMe SSD.
- bs=64M: Block size = 64 megabytes. This makes the copy faster by reading/writing in large chunks instead of tiny blocks.
- status=progress: Shows a live progress bar instead of silently running.
- conv=fsync: Forces dd to flush all data to disk before finishing.

## The clone copies:
boot partition
root filesystem
installed packages
user accounts
system configuration

## 6. Verify the clone

Check the NVMe disk layout:

command: lsblk

Expected:

nvme0n1
├─nvme0n1p1
└─nvme0n1p2

This mirrors the SD card partitions.

## 7. Boot from NVMe

Shutdown the system:

command: sudo poweroff

Remove the SD card.

Power the Pi back on.

The bootloader will now load the system from NVMe.

## 8. Confirm system is running from NVMe

Reconnect via SSH and check:

command: lsblk

Expected:

nvme0n1p1 /boot/firmware
nvme0n1p2 /

The root filesystem should now be:

/dev/nvme0n1p2

## 9. Expand filesystem to full SSD capacity

Because the clone copies the SD layout, the root partition is still ~58GB.

Expand it to use the full disk.

Run:

command: sudo raspi-config

Navigate:

Advanced Options
   → Expand Filesystem

Reboot:

command: sudo reboot

Verify expansion:

command: df -h /

Example result:

Filesystem      Size  Used Avail Use%
/dev/nvme0n1p2  917G  4G   876G   1%
Final Disk Layout
nvme0n1 (1TB)
├─ nvme0n1p1   512M   /boot/firmware
└─ nvme0n1p2   ~917G  /

nvme1n1 (1TB)
└─ unused (future projects)
Benefits of NVMe Boot

## Compared to SD cards:

Storage	Typical speed
SD card	~50 MB/s
NVMe on Pi 5	~400–800 MB/s

## Advantages:

 • faster boot
 • faster package installs
 • higher durability
 • better database performance
 • better reliability for server workloads
